            &lt;p&gt;Time series prediction is a 1D problem and I am skeptical
              about the advantage of HyperNEAT over other methods like
              regular NEAT and other recurrent NN based approaches. It
              seems that a lot of people got to know about HyperNEAT&#39;s
              ability to overcome a lot of challenges and then try to
              apply it to everything, without knowing it&#39;s internal
              workings, mainly the CPPN theory and the way CPPNs
              generate patterns. Trying HyperNEAT on everything is good,
              though, it sheds light on what tasks the algorithm works
              and where it fails. It would be good to know if HyperNEAT
              performs well in time series prediction. Perhaps some kind
              of data preprocessing, which makes geometrical sense,
              should help. I personally have tried time series
              prediction with HyperNEAT and had no better results than
              regular NEAT, even worse. &lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Peter&lt;br&gt;
